Thanks Tim - better angle than when I watched it live with NSF, and the slow motion is brilliant (or awesome, as some might say!).

I suspect (hope) that this isn't as worrying as it might seem, from the NSF camera it looked very lopsided, but from your view it was far more evenly distributed (smoke/steam and debris). Although the NSF camera did show a fire of some sort under the Starship after the Raptors had shut down, which is only just visible in your video.

I guess it can only be one of three things: concrete or whatever being blown off the surface, some part of the stand being destroyed, or some part of an engine or the skirt (or something mounted inside the skirt) being destroyed. My gut feel is that it wasn't concrete, it just doesn't seem to behave the way I would expect concrete to, and I can't think of anything else on the surface that would disintegrate. So that would leave something to do with the stand or rocket disintegrating (and continuing to burn briefly afterwards?). I think it's unlikely to be part of an engine, given all the testing they've had, and that we didn't see or hear anything that sugested engine problems.

Maybe it's just that three Raptors have never been fired together before and the combined blast/heat/turbulance is far more than was expected? And the result was damage that hadn't been expected. If this is the case, it could indicate that even the prototype Starships are going to need a 'proper' launch pad (flame divertors, more effective damping, etc). But it also demonstrates just how powerful these engine are and how difficult it's going to be to fire multiple Raptors together (and the Super Heavy booster is going to have a lot more than three!). I've always suspected that it's not going to be easy to test fire the SH boosters at Boca Chica (even with limited numbers of Raptors), and it's definitely not going to be possible to fly the SH booster (or perhaps even the Starship) to orbit from there.

Edit: looking at the comments, it seems this might have just been ONE Raptor. In which case, I don't want to be anywhere near this thing when they test all three together!!

Everyone's asking about what the sparks were... there's only 4 options i can think of.. 1) the engine ate itself (possible as there seemed to be a brief flame around it at shut-down) 2) some type of ground equipment or test stand let go... there was def 2 different splatter patterns. 3) concrete... there was several gallons of LOX pouring out of the right side "tri-vent" as NasaSpaceflight calls them prior to ignition. this could have thermal shocked the concrete into spalling. and lastly 4) ice build up on said concrete due to the abundance of LOX pouring on the ground. i'm kinda leaning towards ice or concrete only because none of the ejected material (even tho glowing...) seemed to carry any heat/smoke away from the rocket or set any additional fires off on the ground. i guess we'll know more once the sun comes up there and crews go out to look at it. i hope its just ice tho.
